         =20
         =20
<p>Let=E2=80=99s specifically cover this subject. (rimshot!)</p>



<p>The best way to explain it is to start with an example of where specific=
ity gets confusing and perhaps doesn=E2=80=99t behave like you would expect=
. Then we=E2=80=99ll take a closer look at how to calculate the actual spec=
ificity value to determine which selector takes precedence.</p>



<span id=3D"more-855"></span>



<p>Here is a simple unordered list:</p>



<pre rel=3D"HTML" class=3D"wp-block-csstricks-code-block  language-html" da=
ta-line=3D""><code markup=3D"tt" class=3D" language-html"><span class=3D"to=
ken tag"><span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token punctuation">&lt;</=
span>ul</span> <span class=3D"token attr-name">id</span><span class=3D"toke=
n attr-value"><span class=3D"token punctuation">=3D</span><span class=3D"to=
ken punctuation">"</span>summer-drinks<span class=3D"token punctuation">"</=
span></span><span class=3D"token punctuation">&gt;</span></span>
   <span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token=
 punctuation">&lt;</span>li</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">&gt;</s=
pan></span>Whiskey and Ginger Ale<span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"t=
oken tag"><span class=3D"token punctuation">&lt;/</span>li</span><span clas=
s=3D"token punctuation">&gt;</span></span>
   <span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token=
 punctuation">&lt;</span>li</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">&gt;</s=
pan></span>Wheat Beer<span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token tag"><s=
pan class=3D"token punctuation">&lt;/</span>li</span><span class=3D"token p=
unctuation">&gt;</span></span>
   <span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token=
 punctuation">&lt;</span>li</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">&gt;</s=
pan></span>Mint Julip<span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token tag"><s=
pan class=3D"token punctuation">&lt;/</span>li</span><span class=3D"token p=
unctuation">&gt;</span></span>
<span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token pu=
nctuation">&lt;/</span>ul</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">&gt;</spa=
n></span></code></pre>



<p>Now you want to designate one of these your favorite drink and change it=
s styling a bit. You need a hook for this so you apply it via a class name =
on the list element.</p>



<pre rel=3D"HTML" class=3D"wp-block-csstricks-code-block  language-html" da=
ta-line=3D""><code markup=3D"tt" class=3D" language-html"><span class=3D"to=
ken tag"><span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token punctuation">&lt;</=
span>ul</span> <span class=3D"token attr-name">id</span><span class=3D"toke=
n attr-value"><span class=3D"token punctuation">=3D</span><span class=3D"to=
ken punctuation">"</span>summer-drinks<span class=3D"token punctuation">"</=
span></span><span class=3D"token punctuation">&gt;</span></span>
   <span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token=
 punctuation">&lt;</span>li</span> <span class=3D"token attr-name">class</s=
pan><span class=3D"token attr-value"><span class=3D"token punctuation">=3D<=
/span><span class=3D"token punctuation">"</span>favorite<span class=3D"toke=
n punctuation">"</span></span><span class=3D"token punctuation">&gt;</span>=
</span>Whiskey and Ginger Ale<span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token=
 tag"><span class=3D"token punctuation">&lt;/</span>li</span><span class=3D=
"token punctuation">&gt;</span></span>
   <span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token=
 punctuation">&lt;</span>li</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">&gt;</s=
pan></span>Wheat Beer<span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token tag"><s=
pan class=3D"token punctuation">&lt;/</span>li</span><span class=3D"token p=
unctuation">&gt;</span></span>
   <span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token=
 punctuation">&lt;</span>li</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">&gt;</s=
pan></span>Mint Julip<span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token tag"><s=
pan class=3D"token punctuation">&lt;/</span>li</span><span class=3D"token p=
unctuation">&gt;</span></span>
<span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token tag"><span class=3D"token pu=
nctuation">&lt;/</span>ul</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">&gt;</spa=
n></span></code></pre>



<p>Now you pop open your CSS and do your styling for your new class:</p>



<pre rel=3D"CSS" class=3D"wp-block-csstricks-code-block  language-css" data=
-line=3D""><code markup=3D"tt" class=3D" language-css"><span class=3D"token=
 selector"><span class=3D"token class">.favorite</span></span> <span class=
=3D"token punctuation">{</span>
  <span class=3D"token property">color</span><span class=3D"token punctuati=
on">:</span> red<span class=3D"token punctuation">;</span>
  <span class=3D"token property">font-weight</span><span class=3D"token pun=
ctuation">:</span> bold<span class=3D"token punctuation">;</span>
<span class=3D"token punctuation">}</span></code></pre>



<p>Then you take a look at your work, but alas, <em>it didn=E2=80=99t work!=
</em> The text of your favorite drink didn=E2=80=99t turn red or go bold! S=
omething fishy is at work here.</p>



<p>Poking around more in the CSS, you find this:</p>



<pre rel=3D"CSS" class=3D"wp-block-csstricks-code-block  language-css" data=
-line=3D""><code markup=3D"tt" class=3D" language-css"><span class=3D"token=
 selector">ul<span class=3D"token id">#summer-drinks</span> li</span> <span=
 class=3D"token punctuation">{</span>
   <span class=3D"token property">font-weight</span><span class=3D"token pu=
nctuation">:</span> normal<span class=3D"token punctuation">;</span>
   <span class=3D"token property">font-size</span><span class=3D"token punc=
tuation">:</span> <span class=3D"token number">12</span><span class=3D"toke=
n unit">px</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">;</span>
   <span class=3D"token property">color</span><span class=3D"token punctuat=
ion">:</span> black<span class=3D"token punctuation">;</span>
<span class=3D"token punctuation">}</span></code></pre>



<p>There is your trouble right there. Two different CSS selectors are telli=
ng that text what color and font-weight to be. There is only one statement =
for font-size, so clearly that one will take effect. These aren=E2=80=99t =
=E2=80=9Cconflicts=E2=80=9D per-say, but the browser does need to decide wh=
ich one of these statements to honor. It does so by following a standard se=
t of specificity rules.</p>



<p>I think this confuses some beginners because they haven=E2=80=99t quite =
gotten this sorted out yet. They might think because the .favorite statemen=
t is =E2=80=9C<em>further down in the CSS</em>=E2=80=9D or because the clas=
s=3D=E2=80=9Dfavorite=E2=80=9D is =E2=80=9C<em>closer to the actual text</e=
m>=E2=80=9D in the HTML that will be the one that =E2=80=9Cwins=E2=80=9D.</=
p>



<p>In fact, the order of selectors in your CSS does play a role and the =E2=
=80=9Cfurther down=E2=80=9D one does in fact win when the specificity value=
s are exactly the same. For example:</p>



<pre rel=3D"CSS" class=3D"wp-block-csstricks-code-block  language-css" data=
-line=3D""><code markup=3D"tt" class=3D" language-css"><span class=3D"token=
 selector"><span class=3D"token class">.favorite</span></span> <span class=
=3D"token punctuation">{</span>
   <span class=3D"token property">color</span><span class=3D"token punctuat=
ion">:</span> red<span class=3D"token punctuation">;</span>
<span class=3D"token punctuation">}</span>
<span class=3D"token selector"><span class=3D"token class">.favorite</span>=
</span> <span class=3D"token punctuation">{</span>
   <span class=3D"token property">color</span><span class=3D"token punctuat=
ion">:</span> black<span class=3D"token punctuation">;</span>
<span class=3D"token punctuation">}</span></code></pre>



<p>The color will be black=E2=80=A6 but I digress.</p>



<p>The point here is <strong>you want to be as specific as it makes sense t=
o be</strong> every chance you get. Even with the simple example presented =
above, it will become obvious to you eventually that simply using a class n=
ame to target that =E2=80=9Cfavorite drink=E2=80=9D isn=E2=80=99t going to =
cut it, or won=E2=80=99t be very safe even if it did work. It would have be=
en smart to use this:</p>



<pre rel=3D"CSS" class=3D"wp-block-csstricks-code-block  language-css" data=
-line=3D""><code markup=3D"tt" class=3D" language-css"><span class=3D"token=
 selector">ul<span class=3D"token id">#summer-drinks</span> li<span class=
=3D"token class">.favorite</span></span> <span class=3D"token punctuation">=
{</span>
  <span class=3D"token property">color</span><span class=3D"token punctuati=
on">:</span> red<span class=3D"token punctuation">;</span>
  <span class=3D"token property">font-weight</span><span class=3D"token pun=
ctuation">:</span> bold<span class=3D"token punctuation">;</span>
<span class=3D"token punctuation">}</span></code></pre>



<p>That is what I=E2=80=99m calling =E2=80=9Cbeing as specific as it makes =
sense to be=E2=80=9D. You could actually be way more specific and use somet=
hing like this:</p>



<pre rel=3D"CSS" class=3D"wp-block-csstricks-code-block  language-css" data=
-line=3D""><code markup=3D"tt" class=3D" language-css"><span class=3D"token=
 selector">html body div<span class=3D"token id">#pagewrap</span> ul<span c=
lass=3D"token id">#summer-drinks</span> li<span class=3D"token class">.favo=
rite</span></span> <span class=3D"token punctuation">{</span>
  <span class=3D"token property">color</span><span class=3D"token punctuati=
on">:</span> red<span class=3D"token punctuation">;</span>
  <span class=3D"token property">font-weight</span><span class=3D"token pun=
ctuation">:</span> bold<span class=3D"token punctuation">;</span>
<span class=3D"token punctuation">}</span></code></pre>



<p>But that is over the top. It makes your CSS harder to read and yields no=
 real benefits. Another way to juice up the specificity value for your =E2=
=80=9C.favorite=E2=80=9D class is to use the !important declaration.</p>



<pre rel=3D"CSS" class=3D"wp-block-csstricks-code-block  language-css" data=
-line=3D""><code markup=3D"tt" class=3D" language-css"><span class=3D"token=
 selector"><span class=3D"token class">.favorite</span></span> <span class=
=3D"token punctuation">{</span>
  <span class=3D"token property">color</span><span class=3D"token punctuati=
on">:</span> red <span class=3D"token important">!important</span><span cla=
ss=3D"token punctuation">;</span>
  <span class=3D"token property">font-weight</span><span class=3D"token pun=
ctuation">:</span> bold <span class=3D"token important">!important</span><s=
pan class=3D"token punctuation">;</span>
<span class=3D"token punctuation">}</span></code></pre>



<p>I once heard it said that !important is like the Jedi mind trick for CSS=
. Indeed it is, and you can force your will over the styling of elements by=
 using it. But !important imposes that will through drastically increasing =
the specificity of that particular selectors property.</p>



<p>The !important declaration can be easily misused if misunderstood. It is=
 best used to keep your CSS cleaner, in examples where you know elements wi=
th a particular class selector should use a certain set of styling <em>no m=
atter what</em>. Conversely, not used just as a quick crutch to override th=
e styling of something instead of figuring out how the CSS was structured a=
nd working by the original author.</p>



<p>One of my classic examples is:</p>



<pre rel=3D"CSS" class=3D"wp-block-csstricks-code-block  language-css" data=
-line=3D""><code markup=3D"tt" class=3D" language-css"><span class=3D"token=
 selector"><span class=3D"token class">.last</span></span> <span class=3D"t=
oken punctuation">{</span>
   <span class=3D"token property">margin-right</span><span class=3D"token p=
unctuation">:</span> <span class=3D"token number">0</span> <span class=3D"t=
oken important">!important</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">;</span>
<span class=3D"token punctuation">}</span></code></pre>



<p>I often use that in situations where there are multiple floated blocks, =
for the last block on the right in a row. That ensures the last block doesn=
=E2=80=99t have any right margin which would prevent it from butting snugly=
 against the right edge of its parent. Each of those blocks probably has mo=
re specific CSS selectors that apply the right margin to begin with, but !i=
mportant will break through that and take care of it with one simple/clean =
class.</p>


<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-calculating-css-specificity-value"><=
a href=3D"https://css-tricks.com/specifics-on-css-specificity/#aa-calculati=
ng-css-specificity-value" aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"aal_anchor" id=3D"a=
a-calculating-css-specificity-value"><svg aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"aal=
_svg" height=3D"16" version=3D"1.1" viewBox=3D"0 0 16 16" width=3D"16"><pat=
h fill-rule=3D"evenodd" d=3D"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.=
45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22=
 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.9=
8 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-=
2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></sv=
g></a>Calculating CSS Specificity Value</h3>


<p>Why is that our first attempt at changing the color and font-weight fail=
ed? As we learned, it was because simply using the class name by itself had=
 a <em>lower specificity value</em> and was trumped by the other selector w=
hich targeted the unordered list with the ID value. The important words in =
that sentence were <strong>class</strong> and <strong>ID</strong>. CSS appl=
ies vastly different specificity weights to classes and IDs. In fact, an ID=
 has <em>infinitely</em> more specificity value! That is, no amount of clas=
ses alone can outweigh an ID.</p>



<p>Let=E2=80=99s take a look at how the numbers are actually calculated:</p=
>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img decoding=3D"async" fetchpr=
iority=3D"high" width=3D"570" height=3D"346" src=3D"https://i0.wp.com/css-t=
ricks.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/specificity-calculationbase_rhrovi.png=
?resize=3D570%2C346&amp;ssl=3D1" alt=3D"" class=3D"wp-image-333167"></figur=
e>



<p>In otherwords:</p>



<ul><li>If the element has inline styling, that automatically<sup>1</sup> w=
ins (1,0,0,0 points)</li><li>For each ID value, apply 0,1,0,0 points</li><l=
i>For each class value (or pseudo-class or attribute selector), apply 0,0,1=
,0 points</li><li>For each element reference, apply 0,0,0,1 point</li></ul>



<p>You can generally read the values as if they were just a number, like 1,=
0,0,0 is =E2=80=9C1000=E2=80=9D, and so clearly wins over a specificity of =
0,1,0,0 or =E2=80=9C100=E2=80=9D. The commas are there to remind us that th=
is isn=E2=80=99t really a =E2=80=9Cbase 10=E2=80=9D system, in that you cou=
ld technically have a specificity value of like 0,1,13,4 =E2=80=93 and that=
 =E2=80=9C13=E2=80=9D doesn=E2=80=99t spill over like a base 10 system woul=
d.</p>


<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-sample-calculations"><a href=3D"http=
s://css-tricks.com/specifics-on-css-specificity/#aa-sample-calculations" ar=
ia-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"aal_anchor" id=3D"aa-sample-calculations"><svg =
aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"aal_svg" height=3D"16" version=3D"1.1" viewBo=
x=3D"0 0 16 16" width=3D"16"><path fill-rule=3D"evenodd" d=3D"M4 9h1v1H4c-1=
.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8=
.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9z=
m9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-=
1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.6=
9 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Sample calculations</h3>


